The paper focuses on using Deep Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) for accurate detection of sleep/wake patterns using activity data collected from a wearable device. This involves the use of Big Data technologies and advanced analytics methods, which are commonly associated with the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the study involves the use of wearable technology and digital markers for disease management, which falls under the sub-category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper also discusses the potential of using these methods in clinical trials, which is related to the sub-category of cs.CYBER (Cybernetics). Finally, the study explores the relationship between sleep/wake patterns and onset of cluster headache attacks, which could be associated with the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
